{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_5bTOBEqVUhxQVEfiHnHETlg2","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Live prod scenarios\n2\t\n3\tTwo high-complexity, end-to-end scenarios that exercise the **system spaces** (`system-appbuilder`,\n4\t`system-architect`, `system-research`, `system-store`, `system-engineer`) and the **unified event\n5\tpipeline** through the **THING agent**, against the **live production cluster and a live LLM**.\n6\t\n7\tEvery scenario runs as a real user would: a disposable prod test user, a real compute pod, a real\n8\tTHING chat session, real model calls. Nothing is mocked. If a scenario passes, the feature works in\n9\tproduction — not in a unit test.\n10\t\n11\t| # | Scenario | Covers |\n12\t|---|---|---|\n13\t| [05](./05-latam/scenario.md) | **Latin America** — six months, nine countries, one growing project | the full lifecycle: incremental space growth, integrations, a THING-controlled **project app** automating bookings/transport/notifications, live in the project web app |\n14\t| [06](./06-tanzania/scenario.md) | **Tanzania trip** — one attachment becomes spaces + a live, updatable app | file ingest (`system-files`); per-leg spaces; live-project app (`writeProjectTable`/`Page`/`Api` + rows seed); `db:write` later-update; compound + multilingual ask |\n15\t\n16\t## Running one\n17\t\n18\t```bash\n19\tcd sdk/org/scenarios/harness\n20\tnode smoke.mjs                 # prove the harness + prod are healthy first (≈1 min)\n21\tnode ../05-latam/run.mjs        # a scenario's runner writes its own report\n22\t```\n23\t\n24\tEach scenario directory holds a `scenario.md` (the spec) and a `run.mjs` (the executable spec), and\n25\twrites `sdk/org/scenarios/<id>/results/report.md` plus a raw trace JSON. The **Actual results**\n26\tsection of `scenario.md` is pasted back from that report, so the document is both the plan and the\n27\trecord.\n28\t\n29\t## Authoring a new scenario — the format + the workflow\n30\t\n31\tThe full **format** (the six-section `scenario.md` structure, the feature catalog, the validation\n32\tprocess, the harness API) and the **workflow** (run → triage → fix-in-product-with-a-test →\n33\tverify-live → report, plus the image-rebuild loop and multi-hour babysitting discipline) now live,\n34\tself-contained, in the automation instance that drives this campaign:\n35\t[`automation/instances/scenario-campaign/prompt.common.md`](../../../automation/instances/scenario-campaign/prompt.common.md)\n36\t(run it with `node automation/lmauto.mjs run scenario-campaign`).\n37\t\n38\tTo author one by hand, copy the template:\n39\t\n40\t- **[`_template/`](./_template/)** — `cp -r _template <NN-slug>`, then fill **`<NN-slug>/scenario.md`**\n41\t  (the six-section spec with a feature checklist) and **`run.mjs`** (the runner\n42\t  scaffold — checkpoint/resume, keepalive, resilient send, scripted asks, and attachment + live-app +\n43\t  signed-inbound helpers all pre-wired; replace the `SCENARIO_*` config and write the Acts).\n44\t\n45\tTo start: `cp -r _template 07-myscenario`, then fill `07-myscenario/scenario.md` and `run.mjs`.\n46\t\n47\t**Quick start:**\n48\t```bash\n49\tcd sdk/org/scenarios/harness\n50\tnode smoke.mjs                       # prove the harness + prod are healthy (≈1 min)\n51\tnode ../07-myscenario/run.mjs        # run it; writes 07-myscenario/results/report.md\n52\t```\n53\t\n54\t## The harness\n55\t\n56\t`harness/` is zero-dependency Node ESM. It drives the pod's HTTP API directly — no browser needed —\n57\tbecause the pod exposes the whole surface the `/chat` SPA uses (`sdk/org/libs/cli/src/server/`):\n58\t\n59\t```js\n60\timport { getUser } from './provision.mjs';            // register → pod → Azure keys → ready\n61\timport { Pod } from './lib/pod.mjs';                  // projects, files, store, hooks, inbound, app\n62\timport { ThingSession, approveAllConsent } from './lib/thing.mjs';\n63\timport { Report } from './lib/report.mjs';            // → the markdown results table\n64\t\n65\tconst user = await getUser('my-scenario');\n66\tconst pod = new Pod({ base: user.pod, token: user.token });\n67\tconst thing = new ThingSession(pod, { onAsk: approveAllConsent, verbose: true });\n68\tawait thing.start();                                   // POST /api/sessions  (interactive!)\n69\tconst turn = await thing.send('install a slack integration and watch #eng');\n70\t\n71\tturn.delegates;      // ['system-store/finder/…', 'system-appbuilder/automator/…']\n72\tturn.yields;         // every global THING called, incl. installSpace\n73\tturn.tokens;         // { in, out }\n74\tthing.consentCards() // every ConsentCard raised, and how it was answered\n75\t```\n76\t\n77\t### Why assertions read the trace, not the prose\n78\t\n79\tThe pod streams the full execution trace (`libs/core/src/sandbox/trace.ts`), so a scenario asserts on\n80\twhat the agent **did** — which specialist it delegated to, which consent-marked global it called,\n81\twhich yields resolved, which hooks fired, how many tokens it burned — instead of grading a paragraph\n82\tof English. A scenario that only checks the final message is a scenario that passes when the system\n83\tis broken.\n84\t\n85\t### Things the harness learned the hard way\n86\t\n87\t- **Consent needs an interactive session.** The consent prompter is only wired when\n88\t  `POST /api/sessions` created the session. Headless paths (hooks, delegates, webhook dispatch) have\n89\t  no prompter and **fail closed** — that is the designed behaviour (a scenario should assert it, not work around it).\n90\t- **`PUT /api/compute/env` rolls the pod, and sessions are in-memory.** A session created against\n91\t  the old replica dies with it (`404 unknown session`). `provisionUser()` therefore loads env\n92\t  *before* the first turn, skips the PUT when nothing changed, and then proves a session survives\n93\t  before handing the pod over (`waitPodSettled`).\n94\t- **`pod.ready` is `readyReplicas > 0`**, which is true throughout a rolling update and precedes\n95\t  Envoy wiring the new endpoint. Never treat it as \"my next request will land on the new pod\".\n96\t- **The gateway JWT secret is double-base64.** `.data.GATEWAY_JWT_SECRET` in k8s decodes to the env\n97\t  *value*, which is itself base64 of the signing key. Decode once when fetching, once when signing.\n98\t\n99\t## Budget\n100\t\n101\tScenarios burn real tokens. `provisionUser()` loads the **direct Azure** keys from `sdk/org/.env`\n102\tinto the pod env, so agent traffic bypasses the per-user LiteLLM key that carries the tier budget —\n103\ta run cannot be halted by a tier cap mid-scenario. If a pod ever is capped, provision a new user\n104\t(`node provision.mjs <label>`) and re-run; test users are disposable by design.\n105\t\n106\tTest users are named `<label>-<base36-ts>@lmthing.test` and each gets its own `user-<id>` namespace\n107\tand pod. Clean up with `kubectl delete ns user-<id>`.\n108\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e527c9e4-a091-4065-bd58-17ce2dd60e21","uuid":"ba0c323c-d08e-4118-be38-081e7703b42d","timestamp":"2026-07-14T16:40:19.477Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/scenarios/README.md","content":"# Live prod scenarios\n\nTwo high-complexity, end-to-end scenarios that exercise the **system spaces** (`system-appbuilder`,\n`system-architect`, `system-research`, `system-store`, `system-engineer`) and the **unified event\npipeline** through the **THING agent**, against the **live production cluster and a live LLM**.\n\nEvery scenario runs as a real user would: a disposable prod test user, a real compute pod, a real\nTHING chat session, real model calls. Nothing is mocked. If a scenario passes, the feature works in\nproduction — not in a unit test.\n\n| # | Scenario | Covers |\n|---|---|---|\n| [05](./05-latam/scenario.md) | **Latin America** — six months, nine countries, one growing project | the full lifecycle: incremental space growth, integrations, a THING-controlled **project app** automating bookings/transport/notifications, live in the project web app |\n| [06](./06-tanzania/scenario.md) | **Tanzania trip** — one attachment becomes spaces + a live, updatable app | file ingest (`system-files`); per-leg spaces; live-project app (`writeProjectTable`/`Page`/`Api` + rows seed); `db:write` later-update; compound + multilingual ask |\n\n## Running one\n\n```bash\ncd sdk/org/scenarios/harness\nnode smoke.mjs                 # prove the harness + prod are healthy first (≈1 min)\nnode ../05-latam/run.mjs        # a scenario's runner writes its own report\n```\n\nEach scenario directory holds a `scenario.md` (the spec) and a `run.mjs` (the executable spec), and\nwrites `sdk/org/scenarios/<id>/results/report.md` plus a raw trace JSON. The **Actual results**\nsection of `scenario.md` is pasted back from that report, so the document is both the plan and the\nrecord.\n\n## Authoring a new scenario — the format + the workflow\n\nThe full **format** (the six-section `scenario.md` structure, the feature catalog, the validation\nprocess, the harness API) and the **workflow** (run → triage → fix-in-product-with-a-test →\nverify-live → report, plus the image-rebuild loop and multi-hour babysitting discipline) now live,\nself-contained, in the automation instance that drives this campaign:\n[`automation/instances/scenario-campaign/prompt.common.md`](../../../automation/instances/scenario-campaign/prompt.common.md)\n(run it with `node automation/lmauto.mjs run scenario-campaign`).\n\nTo author one by hand, copy the template:\n\n- **[`_template/`](./_template/)** — `cp -r _template <NN-slug>`, then fill **`<NN-slug>/scenario.md`**\n  (the six-section spec with a feature checklist) and **`run.mjs`** (the runner\n  scaffold — checkpoint/resume, keepalive, resilient send, scripted asks, and attachment + live-app +\n  signed-inbound helpers all pre-wired; replace the `SCENARIO_*` config and write the Acts).\n\nTo start: `cp -r _template 07-myscenario`, then fill `07-myscenario/scenario.md` and `run.mjs`.\n\n**Quick start:**\n```bash\ncd sdk/org/scenarios/harness\nnode smoke.mjs                       # prove the harness + prod are healthy (≈1 min)\nnode ../07-myscenario/run.mjs        # run it; writes 07-myscenario/results/report.md\n```\n\n## The harness\n\n`harness/` is zero-dependency Node ESM. It drives the pod's HTTP API directly — no browser needed —\nbecause the pod exposes the whole surface the `/chat` SPA uses (`sdk/org/libs/cli/src/server/`):\n\n```js\nimport { getUser } from './provision.mjs';            // register → pod → Azure keys → ready\nimport { Pod } from './lib/pod.mjs';                  // projects, files, store, hooks, inbound, app\nimport { ThingSession, approveAllConsent } from './lib/thing.mjs';\nimport { Report } from './lib/report.mjs';            // → the markdown results table\n\nconst user = await getUser('my-scenario');\nconst pod = new Pod({ base: user.pod, token: user.token });\nconst thing = new ThingSession(pod, { onAsk: approveAllConsent, verbose: true });\nawait thing.start();                                   // POST /api/sessions  (interactive!)\nconst turn = await thing.send('install a slack integration and watch #eng');\n\nturn.delegates;      // ['system-store/finder/…', 'system-appbuilder/automator/…']\nturn.yields;         // every global THING called, incl. installSpace\nturn.tokens;         // { in, out }\nthing.consentCards() // every ConsentCard raised, and how it was answered\n```\n\n### Why assertions read the trace, not the prose\n\nThe pod streams the full execution trace (`libs/core/src/sandbox/trace.ts`), so a scenario asserts on\nwhat the agent **did** — which specialist it delegated to, which consent-marked global it called,\nwhich yields resolved, which hooks fired, how many tokens it burned — instead of grading a paragraph\nof English. A scenario that only checks the final message is a scenario that passes when the system\nis broken.\n\n### Things the harness learned the hard way\n\n- **Consent needs an interactive session.** The consent prompter is only wired when\n  `POST /api/sessions` created the session. Headless paths (hooks, delegates, webhook dispatch) have\n  no prompter and **fail closed** — that is the designed behaviour (a scenario should assert it, not work around it).\n- **`PUT /api/compute/env` rolls the pod, and sessions are in-memory.** A session created against\n  the old replica dies with it (`404 unknown session`). `provisionUser()` therefore loads env\n  *before* the first turn, skips the PUT when nothing changed, and then proves a session survives\n  before handing the pod over (`waitPodSettled`).\n- **`pod.ready` is `readyReplicas > 0`**, which is true throughout a rolling update and precedes\n  Envoy wiring the new endpoint. Never treat it as \"my next request will land on the new pod\".\n- **The gateway JWT secret is double-base64.** `.data.GATEWAY_JWT_SECRET` in k8s decodes to the env\n  *value*, which is itself base64 of the signing key. Decode once when fetching, once when signing.\n\n## Budget\n\nScenarios burn real tokens. `provisionUser()` loads the **direct Azure** keys from `sdk/org/.env`\ninto the pod env, so agent traffic bypasses the per-user LiteLLM key that carries the tier budget —\na run cannot be halted by a tier cap mid-scenario. If a pod ever is capped, provision a new user\n(`node provision.mjs <label>`) and re-run; test users are disposable by design.\n\nTest users are named `<label>-<base36-ts>@lmthing.test` and each gets its own `user-<id>` namespace\nand pod. Clean up with `kubectl delete ns user-<id>`.\n","numLines":108,"startLine":1,"totalLines":108}}}
